Bobby...

254
00:13:15,751 --> 00:13:18,101
What would you say
if me and my people

255
00:13:18,275 --> 00:13:19,668
offered to buy this ranch?

256
00:13:19,842 --> 00:13:23,106
- [Sighs]
Well, that's...

257
00:13:23,280 --> 00:13:25,456
that's nice of you, Cody.

258
00:13:25,630 --> 00:13:29,069
But, uh...I guess
I'd have to say no.

259
00:13:29,243 --> 00:13:32,724
- That's it?
Just no?

260
00:13:32,899 --> 00:13:34,944
- Same thing his father said

261
00:13:35,118 --> 00:13:37,947
when he asked you
to leave the property, Cody.

262
00:13:38,121 --> 00:13:40,515
- You really might want
to think about it, Bobby.

263
00:13:40,689 --> 00:13:43,474
- Why don't you go on
in the house, honey.

264
00:13:43,648 --> 00:13:44,606
- Or she can come with me.

265
00:13:44,780 --> 00:13:47,696
- Let's go.

266
00:13:47,870 --> 00:13:49,567
- Think about it, will ya,
Bobby?

267
00:13:49,741 --> 00:13:51,613
Make you a good offer.

268
00:13:56,444 --> 00:13:57,793
- Cody McMichael.

269
00:13:57,967 --> 00:13:59,882
I actually dated him
when I got here

270
00:14:00,056 --> 00:14:02,842
'til I found out
he was married.

271
00:14:03,016 --> 00:14:05,322
Looking back, I suspect
all he really wanted

272
00:14:05,496 --> 00:14:07,281
was to buy my land.

273
00:14:07,455 --> 00:14:10,327
You know, your grandfather
and I had a great connection...

274
00:14:10,501 --> 00:14:12,547
the horses.

275
00:14:12,721 --> 00:14:15,593
Your dad did a good thing
coming back.

276
00:14:15,767 --> 00:14:18,509
- You think so?
I didn't want to come.

277
00:14:18,683 --> 00:14:20,381
This place is so Hicksville.

278
00:14:20,555 --> 00:14:24,559
- Well, not everybody
can live in Los Angeles.

279
00:14:24,733 --> 00:14:26,169
Not everybody wants to.

280
00:14:31,131 --> 00:14:36,310
- Well, it took you a while,
old man.

281
00:14:36,484 --> 00:14:38,834
But you finally got me
back here.

282
00:14:46,059 --> 00:14:47,582
Hey, Hank.

283
00:14:47,756 --> 00:14:52,369
Look at this.

284
00:14:52,543 --> 00:14:54,545
- What is that?

285
00:14:54,719 --> 00:14:57,809
- Core samples.

286
00:14:57,984 --> 00:15:01,030
Somebody's been dry drilling.

287
00:15:01,204 --> 00:15:04,729
My father ever hire any
surveyors to test for a well?

288
00:15:04,904 --> 00:15:07,254
- No. Not that I know of.

289
00:15:09,038 --> 00:15:11,345
- Well, we better get back
and start unpacking.

290
00:15:18,787 --> 00:15:20,920
- Hey.
- Hey, Emily.

291
00:15:21,094 --> 00:15:23,444
[Goat bleats]

292
00:15:23,618 --> 00:15:26,403
- Well, I see you two have met.

293
00:15:26,577 --> 00:15:29,754
Tim helps me out around here.

294
00:15:29,929 --> 00:15:30,973
How's our goat?

295
00:15:31,147 --> 00:15:32,757
- Sneezing up a storm.

296
00:15:32,932 --> 00:15:36,805
- All right. Here we go.

297
00:15:36,979 --> 00:15:38,633
Yeah, I know.
Just like me when I was a kid.

298
00:15:38,807 --> 00:15:39,939
Didn't like my medicine.

299
00:15:40,113 --> 00:15:42,115
- [Groans]
- Ok.

300
00:15:42,289 --> 00:15:43,812
[Goat bleats]
All right, all right.

301
00:15:43,986 --> 00:15:45,727
Good boy, good boy.
There you go.

302
00:15:45,901 --> 00:15:46,946
You want to pet him?

303
00:15:52,734 --> 00:15:53,778
[Goat sneezes]

304
00:16:01,482 --> 00:16:03,919
- It's just a little goat snot.
Not a big deal.

305
00:16:05,616 --> 00:16:06,966
There you go.

306
00:16:08,489 --> 00:16:10,273
- Why don't you give
Madison the tour?

307
00:16:22,068 --> 00:16:24,984
- You coming?
[Goat bleats]

308
00:16:28,074 --> 00:16:31,599
[Clock ticking]

309
00:16:36,952 --> 00:16:41,478
- Oh! Leave that door open,
please.

310
00:16:41,652 --> 00:16:42,653
It's a nice spot, huh?

311
00:16:42,827 --> 00:16:44,481
- Perfect timing.

312
00:16:44,655 --> 00:16:46,701
I already got your computer,
your stereo

313
00:16:46,875 --> 00:16:47,615
and your TV set up
in your room.

314
00:16:47,789 --> 00:16:49,051
Did you have fun?

315
00:16:49,225 --> 00:16:50,531
I want you to see something.

316
00:16:50,705 --> 00:16:51,880
Come on.
- What?

317
00:16:52,054 --> 00:16:55,014
- Come on!
- What is it?

318
00:17:06,025 --> 00:17:08,940
- What do you think?
[Laughs]

319
00:17:09,115 --> 00:17:10,899
- Well, it's water.

320
00:17:11,073 --> 00:17:15,643
- [Laughs] This used to be
my favorite spot.

321
00:17:15,817 --> 00:17:17,558
Yep.

322
00:17:17,732 --> 00:17:18,907
- What are you doing?

323
00:17:19,081 --> 00:17:19,864
- I'm going in.
You coming?

324
00:17:20,039 --> 00:17:21,736
- I don't think so.

325
00:17:21,910 --> 00:17:25,870
- All right! Whoo!

326
00:17:26,045 --> 00:17:27,742
[Splashes]

327
00:17:27,916 --> 00:17:28,917
- [Laughs]
- Whoo!

328
00:17:29,091 --> 00:17:32,573
Whoa! That's the good life!

329
00:17:32,747 --> 00:17:34,053
Come on in!

330
00:17:34,227 --> 00:17:35,532
- No, no. There's leeches
in there.

331
00:17:35,706 --> 00:17:37,534
Bloodsuckers. It's gross.

332
00:17:37,708 --> 00:17:39,928
- Oh yeah! One's got me!
A great big one!

333
00:17:40,102 --> 00:17:42,061
[Splashing]

334
00:17:42,235 --> 00:17:44,193
Oh! You better come in
and save me!

335
00:17:44,367 --> 00:17:46,978
- Dad! [Laughing]
- It's got me! Come help me!

336
00:17:47,153 --> 00:17:49,024
I can't believe he kept
all this stuff.

337
00:17:51,026 --> 00:17:51,896
- Your mom was pretty.

338
00:17:52,071 --> 00:17:54,508
- Yep.

339
00:17:54,682 --> 00:17:56,814
- [Laughs]

340
00:17:56,988 --> 00:17:59,643
And you do look like your dad.

341
00:18:06,911 --> 00:18:08,304
- I got to finish
unpacking.

342
00:18:08,478 --> 00:18:10,001
You might want to email
your friend dawn,

343
00:18:10,176 --> 00:18:11,829
tell her you're here.

344
00:18:12,003 --> 00:18:15,050
Just try not to make it sound
too horrible, all right?

345
00:19:11,933 --> 00:19:13,891
[Horse flutters]

346
00:19:20,463 --> 00:19:21,812
- Do you know what's
going to happen to you?

347
00:19:21,986 --> 00:19:24,598
Do you? Eat. Eat!

348
00:19:24,772 --> 00:19:28,471
Eat. There you go.
Good girl.

349
00:19:30,691 --> 00:19:33,172
- Sorry, didn't mean
to scare you.

350
00:19:33,346 --> 00:19:35,043
Your daddy used to
come down here at night

351
00:19:35,217 --> 00:19:37,132
and do the very same thing.

352
00:19:40,440 --> 00:19:42,746
You know when your dad
left the ranch here,

353
00:19:42,920 --> 00:19:45,923
your grandpa,
it broke his heart,

354
00:19:46,097 --> 00:19:48,056
and he never got over it.

355
00:19:48,230 --> 00:19:50,014
- What about the ultimatum?

356
00:19:50,189 --> 00:19:53,104
- Hot air.

357
00:19:53,279 --> 00:19:55,542
- Well, he could have called.

358
00:19:55,716 --> 00:19:57,631
- Your daddy could have
just called, too.

359
00:20:00,329 --> 00:20:04,159
Well, I'll see you
in the morning.

360
00:20:09,295 --> 00:20:11,558
- Dear dawn, well,

361
00:20:11,732 --> 00:20:13,560
I guess the good news here
is that even though

362
00:20:13,734 --> 00:20:15,779
the hillbillies who named
my dad interim sheriff

363
00:20:15,953 --> 00:20:18,217
got him to come out here
and take over for his father,

364
00:20:18,391 --> 00:20:20,044
I don't think they'll
convince him to stay.

365
00:20:20,219 --> 00:20:23,222
[Clicking keys]

366
00:20:25,746 --> 00:20:28,792
Dear dawn,
you'll think I've gone crazy,

367
00:20:28,966 --> 00:20:31,447
but here it is:
This place is beautiful,

368
00:20:31,621 --> 00:20:33,754
and the people have been
really nice so far.

369
00:20:33,928 --> 00:20:35,103
We live in a big farmhouse
with tons of room.

370
00:20:35,277 --> 00:20:39,325
[Clicking]

371
00:20:39,499 --> 00:20:41,762
I've been giving my dad
plenty of space

372
00:20:41,936 --> 00:20:46,201
because he's figuring out some
things about his own father.

373
00:20:46,375 --> 00:20:49,248
I hope he knows I'm here
for him if he needs me.

374
00:20:53,382 --> 00:20:56,037
And you won't believe this,
dawn,

375
00:20:56,211 --> 00:20:58,126
but there are mustangs,
wild mustangs,

376
00:20:58,300 --> 00:21:00,781
living here on our property.

377
00:21:00,955 --> 00:21:05,046
It rocks! They're the most
beautiful things I've ever seen.

378
00:21:05,220 --> 00:21:07,875
I'll talk to you soon, Madison.

379
00:21:10,051 --> 00:21:12,271
- [Sighs]

380
00:21:15,970 --> 00:21:17,276
[Clock ticking]

381
00:22:02,408 --> 00:22:05,324
[Rooster crows]

382
00:22:07,413 --> 00:22:08,936
[Horse neighs]

383
00:22:12,548 --> 00:22:14,985
[Horse snorts and neighs]

384
00:22:37,965 --> 00:22:39,270
- Now there's a sheriff.

385
00:22:39,445 --> 00:22:41,490
- [Laughs]
She needs to learn how

386
00:22:41,664 --> 00:22:43,449
to clean out the stalls
and feed the animals.

387
00:22:43,623 --> 00:22:45,146
And then she can help you
mend that fence.

388
00:22:45,320 --> 00:22:47,931
- Ok, but if you want
my advice...

389
00:22:48,105 --> 00:22:49,455
- I'll ask for it.

390
00:22:49,629 --> 00:22:51,282
- Seven letter word
for slave.

391
00:22:51,457 --> 00:22:53,459
- What?
- Chattel.

392
00:22:53,633 --> 00:22:55,939
- [Laughs] Chores.
That's living on a ranch.

393
00:22:56,113 --> 00:22:57,724
Have a good one!

394
00:23:04,426 --> 00:23:06,167
- Now listen here, little lady,

395
00:23:06,341 --> 00:23:08,561
you saddle up old Rio here
and take him out for a ride.

396
00:23:08,735 --> 00:23:11,259
But be back
before your dad gets back.

397
00:23:11,433 --> 00:23:15,481
That's right. You don't know
how to ride, do you?

398
00:23:15,655 --> 00:23:19,180
I'll show you.
Grab that blanket there.

399
00:23:19,354 --> 00:23:21,225
Saddle 'em up.
The one under the brush.

400
00:23:21,400 --> 00:23:24,011
That's it.

401
00:23:24,185 --> 00:23:25,882
Try it again.

402
00:23:26,056 --> 00:23:28,102
All right. Here.

403
00:23:28,276 --> 00:23:29,756
Pull her in front of me.

404
00:23:32,323 --> 00:23:36,415
What happened to that?
[Grunts]

405
00:23:40,549 --> 00:23:43,639
Ok. Pull up!
Good, good, good.

406
00:23:46,076 --> 00:23:48,296
This here,
give it a little tap.

407
00:23:48,470 --> 00:23:49,645
Give it a little kick.

408
00:23:52,082 --> 00:23:53,780
- [Screams]
[Thud]

409
00:23:57,479 --> 00:24:01,091
- Oh. You ok?
[Laughs]

410
00:24:01,265 --> 00:24:04,225
- Yeah.
- All right. Whoa.

411
00:24:04,399 --> 00:24:06,009
Hop on.

412
00:24:11,319 --> 00:24:13,364
Good for you.

413
00:24:13,539 --> 00:24:17,151
All right.

414
00:24:17,325 --> 00:24:19,458
[Horse neighs]

415
00:24:44,526 --> 00:24:47,268
[Crickets chirping]

416
00:24:53,492 --> 00:24:55,058
[Clock ticking]

417
00:25:51,114 --> 00:25:52,551
[Keys clicking]

418
00:26:07,783 --> 00:26:10,917
[Wolf howls]

419
00:26:21,797 --> 00:26:24,583
[Wolves howling]

420
00:26:28,587 --> 00:26:30,980
[Thunder claps]

421
00:26:44,254 --> 00:26:49,129
[Thunder clap]

422
00:27:13,719 --> 00:27:16,417
[Sobbing]

423
00:27:17,853 --> 00:27:21,378
[Thunder clap]

424
00:27:23,642 --> 00:27:25,252
[Sobbing harder]

425
00:27:35,610 --> 00:27:37,612
[Rain pattering]

426
00:27:41,747 --> 00:27:45,402
[Thunder clap]

427
00:27:45,576 --> 00:27:46,316
[Light switch clicks]

428
00:27:54,194 --> 00:27:55,630
[Thunder clap]

429
00:27:55,804 --> 00:27:58,894
[Birds tweeting]
[Rooster crows]

430
00:28:08,904 --> 00:28:09,731
- I, uh...

431
00:28:09,905 --> 00:28:13,169
[Rooster crows]

432
00:28:13,343 --> 00:28:16,042
- What?
- I, uh...

433
00:28:16,216 --> 00:28:17,434
Heard something last night.

434
00:28:17,608 --> 00:28:19,567
- Yeah?
- A wolf.

435
00:28:19,741 --> 00:28:21,612
- A wolf?
- Yeah.

436
00:28:21,787 --> 00:28:25,399
Yeah, I saw it, too.
- Huh.

437
00:28:25,573 --> 00:28:27,836
- It was amazing.
- I didn't hear anything.

438
00:28:28,010 --> 00:28:31,144
But, when I was a boy,
I saw some wolves.

439
00:28:31,318 --> 00:28:33,581
They are amazing
and dangerous.

440
00:28:37,324 --> 00:28:39,065
Hey, where'd you get that?
[Laughs]

441
00:28:39,239 --> 00:28:40,283
- Found it.

442
00:28:40,457 --> 00:28:42,155
[Door squeaks open]

443
00:28:42,329 --> 00:28:46,594
- Bob? We got ourselves
a situation.

444
00:28:46,768 --> 00:28:49,728
One of the horses
has been killed.

445
00:28:52,252 --> 00:28:54,733
Wolves don't usually
come down this far.

446
00:28:54,907 --> 00:28:56,647
Out of the mountains.

447
00:28:56,822 --> 00:29:01,348
We had a drought winter
last year, and they're hungry.

448
00:29:01,522 --> 00:29:03,437
There they are.

449
00:29:03,611 --> 00:29:06,353
We're gonna have to
track 'em down, put 'em down.

450
00:29:06,527 --> 00:29:08,181
- Put 'em down?

451
00:29:08,355 --> 00:29:11,097
- These animals are
our responsibility, Madison.

452
00:29:11,271 --> 00:29:13,099
- I know that, but how do we
know that wolves did this?

453
00:29:13,273 --> 00:29:15,101
- What?
- You're a cop.

454
00:29:15,275 --> 00:29:16,450
Don't you need a little bit
more evidence

455
00:29:16,624 --> 00:29:17,886
before making an arrest?

456
00:29:18,060 --> 00:29:19,583
- Don't get all wound up,
all right?

457
00:29:19,758 --> 00:29:22,499
- I'm not. I'm just saying
how can we be 100% sure.

458
00:29:22,673 --> 00:29:25,241
- The cuts there are
the result of strong jaws

459
00:29:25,415 --> 00:29:26,590
and sharp teeth.

460
00:29:26,765 --> 00:29:30,856
- Ok. Say it was wolves.

461
00:29:31,030 --> 00:29:33,249
Isn't there something else
we can do besides killing them?

462
00:29:33,423 --> 00:29:35,251
- Are you representing
the wolves here?

463
00:29:35,425 --> 00:29:36,687
- No one else is.

464
00:29:36,862 --> 00:29:38,646
- Well, I'm representing
the horses.

465
00:29:40,604 --> 00:29:43,433
- Ok, say it was wolves.

466
00:29:43,607 --> 00:29:46,262
Isn't there something else
we can do besides killing them?

467
00:29:46,436 --> 00:29:49,875
- Ah...yeah.

468
00:29:50,049 --> 00:29:52,703
There's a possibility
Emily could come out

469
00:29:52,878 --> 00:29:55,358
with a tranquilizer gun
and we could tranquilize it

470
00:29:55,532 --> 00:29:56,446
and take it up to the mountains
and let it go.

471
00:29:56,620 --> 00:29:58,274
- Let's do that.

472
00:29:58,448 --> 00:29:59,406
- Well, there's no guarantee

473
00:29:59,580 --> 00:30:00,929
it won't come back down.

474
00:30:01,103 --> 00:30:02,496
- Well, let's give it
a try anyway.

475
00:30:02,670 --> 00:30:03,323
- All right.
- All right?

476
00:30:03,497 --> 00:30:04,759
- Yeah, ok.

477
00:30:06,848 --> 00:30:08,067
- Did you know that my wife

478
00:30:08,241 --> 00:30:10,156
and Gus exchanged letters?
- Yep.

479
00:30:10,330 --> 00:30:11,548
- That's all you're
going to say... "yep"?

480
00:30:11,722 --> 00:30:14,725
- She wrote him
her first letter.

481
00:30:14,900 --> 00:30:17,163
But she called it
her olive branch.

482
00:30:17,337 --> 00:30:20,035
Made him a happy man.

483
00:30:51,023 --> 00:30:51,850
[Gun bolt unlocks]

484
00:31:02,382 --> 00:31:03,949
- What do you think, Hank?

485
00:31:04,123 --> 00:31:07,430
- I think this is as good
a place as any to start.

486
00:31:07,604 --> 00:31:09,563
- All right.
- Trailhead's right up here.

487
00:31:09,737 --> 00:31:11,173
- Let's go.

488
00:31:13,088 --> 00:31:14,524
- It's a guy thing.

489
00:31:16,048 --> 00:31:17,484
- Madison, you kids
stay by the truck.

490
00:31:17,658 --> 00:31:18,877
- Dad, I...

491
00:31:19,051 --> 00:31:20,922
- stay by the truck.

492
00:31:21,096 --> 00:31:24,621
- Dad, Iâ€™m...
- stay by the truck.

493
00:31:24,795 --> 00:31:27,450
- It's an adult thing.

494
00:31:38,853 --> 00:31:40,463
- [Sighs]

495
00:31:40,637 --> 00:31:42,901
- Do those tranquilizer darts
hurt?

496
00:31:47,601 --> 00:31:48,907
Better not hurt.

497
00:31:52,562 --> 00:31:54,390
- [Laughs]

498
00:31:54,564 --> 00:31:55,783
[Slaps knee]

499
00:31:55,957 --> 00:31:58,046
There's a dance this weekend.

500
00:31:58,220 --> 00:32:00,570
- What, like, a hoedown
in some barn?

501
00:32:00,744 --> 00:32:02,355
- [Laughs]
No, hoedown, no.

502
00:32:02,529 --> 00:32:05,793
Well, yeah, but it's not
in a barn.

503
00:32:05,967 --> 00:32:07,664
It's at the community center.

504
00:32:07,838 --> 00:32:10,015
It's a really big deal.
It's the fourth of July dance.

505
00:32:10,189 --> 00:32:12,408
I mean, I go every year.
It's a lot of fun.

506
00:32:12,582 --> 00:32:15,759
Dancing, punch, hayrides...
it's pretty great.

507
00:32:15,934 --> 00:32:17,239
You gonna go?

508
00:32:19,981 --> 00:32:22,244
Madison, your dad said
to stay in the truck!

509
00:32:25,813 --> 00:32:27,771
[Sighs]

510
00:32:44,049 --> 00:32:44,658
- Going to the dance tonight?

511
00:32:44,832 --> 00:32:48,618
- I don't dance.

512
00:32:48,792 --> 00:32:50,490
- Wasn't talking to you.

513
00:32:57,062 --> 00:32:59,803
- I don't believe that
my wolves killed that horse.

514
00:32:59,978 --> 00:33:02,328
- Then what? A bobcat?

515
00:33:02,502 --> 00:33:04,634
Why don't you think
it was wolves?

516
00:33:04,808 --> 00:33:08,725
- Just last night
when I saw that wolf,

517
00:33:08,899 --> 00:33:10,292
and I heard it howl...

518
00:33:10,466 --> 00:33:12,903
- yeah, wolves don't howl.
Coyotes howl.

519
00:33:13,078 --> 00:33:14,905
- All right, excuse me.
Let me have my moment.

520
00:33:15,080 --> 00:33:18,518
When the wolf made its sound,

521
00:33:18,692 --> 00:33:22,304
it... it's hard to explain...
but it was wonderful.

522
00:33:22,478 --> 00:33:24,002
Like... like the wolf
was talking to me, you know,

523
00:33:24,176 --> 00:33:25,046
like right to me.

524
00:33:25,220 --> 00:33:28,006
We had a connection.

525
00:33:28,180 --> 00:33:30,008
- I think you watch
too much TV.

526
00:33:32,880 --> 00:33:34,795
[Laughs]

527
00:34:00,821 --> 00:34:03,824
[Wolf howls]

528
00:34:21,972 --> 00:34:24,279
- Madison, why aren't you
back at the truck?

529
00:34:26,847 --> 00:34:27,674
- Dad, look!

530
00:34:27,848 --> 00:34:30,546
[Snarling]

531
00:34:30,720 --> 00:34:32,070
[Gunshot]
[Thud]

532
00:34:32,244 --> 00:34:33,810
[Wolf whines]

533
00:34:51,611 --> 00:34:54,701
- She's all right.
She's got a broken leg, though.

534
00:34:54,875 --> 00:34:57,530
- Broken leg.

535
00:34:57,704 --> 00:35:00,663
[Whining and barking]

536
00:35:05,755 --> 00:35:08,976
- Madison.

537
00:35:09,150 --> 00:35:10,412
What am I gonna do with her?

538
00:35:15,330 --> 00:35:17,811
[Whining and barking]

539
00:35:17,985 --> 00:35:20,030
- Oh, hello.
Hello there.

540
00:35:20,205 --> 00:35:21,467
I'm so sorry about
your mom.

541
00:35:21,641 --> 00:35:25,514
Come on, come on.
All right, come on.

542
00:35:29,214 --> 00:35:30,867
[Whining]

543
00:35:31,041 --> 00:35:34,915
- Hello. Hello, hello.

544
00:35:41,661 --> 00:35:43,750
- Ok.

545
00:35:49,016 --> 00:35:53,238
Built this last year
when I had an injured bobcat.

546
00:35:53,412 --> 00:35:56,632
She's gonna be fine.
Wolves are very adaptable.

547
00:35:56,806 --> 00:35:58,634
That's why they've been able to
live alongside us for so long.

548
00:35:58,808 --> 00:35:59,896
We're their most dangerous
predator.

549
00:36:00,070 --> 00:36:02,029
- [Laughs]
Aw, look.

550
00:36:02,203 --> 00:36:03,987
They're just like little babies.

551
00:36:08,340 --> 00:36:11,865
Well, Emily, Tim and I
are gonna look out for them

552
00:36:12,039 --> 00:36:12,996
and feed them and whatever.

553
00:36:14,128 --> 00:36:15,956
- Well, they're not pets, honey.

554
00:36:16,130 --> 00:36:17,436
So don't get too attached.

555
00:36:17,610 --> 00:36:18,959
Before you know it
they're going to be

556
00:36:19,133 --> 00:36:20,178
back out in the wild
where they belong.

557
00:36:22,223 --> 00:36:25,400
Come on, Hank.
Let's get back.

558
00:36:32,842 --> 00:36:34,757
- Hey, hi.

559
00:36:34,931 --> 00:36:40,459
[Country fiddle music]

560
00:36:40,633 --> 00:36:41,677
- Ho!

561
00:36:41,851 --> 00:36:45,159
- [Laughs]

562
00:36:45,333 --> 00:36:47,901
[Laughter]
- Oh, well, all right.

563
00:36:48,075 --> 00:36:49,990
[Muted conversation]

564
00:36:56,779 --> 00:37:00,870
- [Whistling]

565
00:37:01,044 --> 00:37:02,220
Are you sure you don't
want to dance?

566
00:37:04,309 --> 00:37:07,050
I think you do.
Come on.

567
00:37:07,225 --> 00:37:08,530
- Uh-uh.
[Laughs]

568
00:37:14,319 --> 00:37:16,712
[Laughs]

569
00:37:16,886 --> 00:37:18,279
- Hi.
- Hey.

570
00:37:18,453 --> 00:37:19,889
- Hey.

571
00:37:20,063 --> 00:37:21,717
- Hey. Happy fourth.

572
00:37:21,891 --> 00:37:25,199
- Well, hi.
Yeah, you too.

573
00:37:25,373 --> 00:37:27,027
- She's a great kid.
- Thanks.

574
00:37:27,201 --> 00:37:28,158
- You don't have any problem
with her

575
00:37:28,333 --> 00:37:30,291
helping me out with the wolves?

576
00:37:30,465 --> 00:37:33,468
- Is that Arliss's oldest?
Jess?

577
00:37:35,514 --> 00:37:38,734
- Uh, yeah.
Cody's wife. Poor thing.

578
00:37:38,908 --> 00:37:40,040
- [Laughs]

579
00:37:43,348 --> 00:37:44,610
[Kissing sounds]
- Take care.

580
00:37:46,307 --> 00:37:49,963
- I'm going to go
say hey to Sam.

581
00:37:50,137 --> 00:37:52,226
Hey, Sam.
- Hey, Bobby.

582
00:37:52,400 --> 00:37:53,749
- Happy fourth.
- Happy fourth.

583
00:37:53,923 --> 00:37:55,229
It's a good one, huh?
- It sure is.

584
00:37:55,403 --> 00:37:56,796
Everybody's having
a high time.

585
00:37:56,970 --> 00:37:57,927
- Indeed.
- How you doing? All right?

586
00:37:58,101 --> 00:38:00,060
- Real good, real good.

587
00:38:00,234 --> 00:38:01,061
[Cell phone rings]
How about yourself?

588
00:38:01,235 --> 00:38:01,975
- All right. Hang on.

589
00:38:02,149 --> 00:38:04,630
Yeah, Bob hart?

590
00:38:04,804 --> 00:38:06,022
I can't hear you.

591
00:38:10,505 --> 00:38:12,768
Yeah, I'll be right there.

592
00:38:12,942 --> 00:38:14,857
[Closes phone]

593
00:38:15,031 --> 00:38:16,946
Sam?

594
00:38:17,120 --> 00:38:18,600
Your place is on fire.

595
00:38:22,387 --> 00:38:25,781
[Sirens]

596
00:38:25,955 --> 00:38:32,310
[People chattering]

597
00:38:33,789 --> 00:38:36,662
- Poor Sam.

598
00:38:36,836 --> 00:38:38,359
Must have left some
machinery on or something.

599
00:38:38,533 --> 00:38:40,187
That wouldn't be
the first time.

600
00:38:40,361 --> 00:38:42,494
He's getting on,
that old codger.

601
00:38:42,668 --> 00:38:43,973
- About the same age as you,
isn't he?

602
00:38:44,147 --> 00:38:46,193
- [Laughs]

603
00:38:46,367 --> 00:38:48,195
- He didn't have any insurance.
- Oh, the fool.

604
00:38:48,369 --> 00:38:51,241
I told him, "Sam, you better
start taking care of yourself."

605
00:38:51,416 --> 00:38:53,983
Well, we'll all give him a hand,
of course.

606
00:38:54,157 --> 00:38:55,985
- Yeah, we'll start
investigating tomorrow.

607
00:38:56,159 --> 00:38:59,032
- Investigating?
- Arson is a crime, arliss.

608
00:38:59,206 --> 00:39:01,817
- Bobby, I told you before.
This ain't no los ang-eles.

609
00:39:01,991 --> 00:39:04,994
I mean, people here don't
go setting fires.

610
00:39:05,168 --> 00:39:06,822
- If that's the case,
we'll know for sure.

611
00:39:06,996 --> 00:39:07,780
- [Laughs]

612
00:39:07,954 --> 00:39:09,782
[Goat bleats]

613
00:39:09,956 --> 00:39:12,219
- How you feeling?

614
00:39:12,393 --> 00:39:14,917
Hope you're not in any pain.

615
00:39:15,091 --> 00:39:16,876
Don't worry about
your babies.

616
00:39:17,050 --> 00:39:18,921
They'll be just fine,
I promise.

617
00:39:19,095 --> 00:39:22,142
Now...

618
00:39:22,316 --> 00:39:26,146
You didn't have anything
to do with that horse, did you?

619
00:39:26,320 --> 00:39:29,323
- You're expecting her
to answer?

620
00:39:31,369 --> 00:39:36,199
Madison, why are you
mad at me?

621
00:39:36,374 --> 00:39:38,158
[Wolf growls]

622
00:39:38,332 --> 00:39:39,942
- So maybe I'm not so tough,
ok.

623
00:39:40,116 --> 00:39:42,423
[Wolf whining]

624
00:39:42,597 --> 00:39:44,164
- What do you want
to know about me?

625
00:39:46,296 --> 00:39:49,343
School's out on a Friday.

626
00:39:49,517 --> 00:39:51,301
And then my parents
put me on a bus straight away.

627
00:39:51,476 --> 00:39:53,347
They can't wait until Saturday.
It has to be Friday.

628
00:39:53,521 --> 00:39:57,395
And then I spend my summer
up here.

629
00:39:57,569 --> 00:39:59,092
- You two, I've got to
check a couple of sows

630
00:39:59,266 --> 00:40:01,094
over at old man burns',
and you'd be a big help.

631
00:40:01,268 --> 00:40:04,097
Won't take too long, and I can
drop you off at home after that.

632
00:40:04,271 --> 00:40:06,795
- Ok, em.

633
00:40:06,969 --> 00:40:08,406
Here you go.

634
00:40:14,063 --> 00:40:15,674
[Barking]

635
00:40:15,848 --> 00:40:18,111
- So you sure your dad
is ok with you being here?

636
00:40:18,285 --> 00:40:20,983
- Yeah. No problem.

637
00:40:21,157 --> 00:40:23,159
Come on.
Come on.

638
00:40:28,077 --> 00:40:32,168
[Panting]

639
00:40:35,694 --> 00:40:39,306
- I didn't leave
anything on, Bobby.

640
00:40:39,480 --> 00:40:41,308
At least, I don't think so.

641
00:40:41,482 --> 00:40:45,443
You want some advice.
Don't get old, ok.

642
00:40:48,271 --> 00:40:50,970
[Sighs] Maybe I should have
sold out when I had the chance.

643
00:40:51,144 --> 00:40:53,407
- To whom?
- That mall, you know.

644
00:40:53,581 --> 00:40:57,237
Maybe I should have.
- Hmm.

645
00:40:57,411 --> 00:41:00,240
- [Sighs]

646
00:41:03,983 --> 00:41:07,813
- [Sighs] You know how I
heard about my mom?

647
00:41:07,987 --> 00:41:10,206
TV.

648
00:41:10,380 --> 00:41:12,295
When I tried to ask
my dad questions,

649
00:41:12,470 --> 00:41:15,168
and he'd get mad
and quiet

650
00:41:15,342 --> 00:41:16,343
so I stopped asking.

651
00:41:16,517 --> 00:41:19,346
I figured he was mad at me.

652
00:41:19,520 --> 00:41:22,001
And now it doesn't seem
like he's mad anymore

653
00:41:22,175 --> 00:41:24,394
or not at me anyhow.

654
00:41:24,569 --> 00:41:28,137
And I just... I just want
to hold him.

655
00:41:30,444 --> 00:41:33,316
[Laughs]
Look at these guys.

656
00:41:33,491 --> 00:41:35,449
I bet you're a good mom.

657
00:41:39,192 --> 00:41:42,238
My mom was great.

658
00:41:44,153 --> 00:41:47,287
[Laughs]

659
00:41:50,159 --> 00:41:53,815
[Typing slowly]

660
00:41:53,989 --> 00:41:56,296
- Glenda?

661
00:41:56,470 --> 00:41:57,340
Something doesn't smell right.

662
00:41:57,515 --> 00:42:00,256
- Mildew.

663
00:42:00,430 --> 00:42:03,085
Or is it my egg salad sandwich?

664
00:42:03,259 --> 00:42:05,087
[Phone ringing]

665
00:42:05,261 --> 00:42:07,089
- Hello? Hillridge
land development.

666
00:42:07,263 --> 00:42:09,265
- Yeah, this is sheriff Bob hart
from hope.

667
00:42:09,439 --> 00:42:11,224
- Oh, hi.
How can I help you, sheriff?

668
00:42:11,398 --> 00:42:15,184
- I need to talk to somebody
about the hope town center mall.

669
00:42:15,358 --> 00:42:16,446
- One moment, please.

670
00:42:16,621 --> 00:42:18,144
[Smack]

671
00:42:20,102 --> 00:42:21,103
- [Sighs]

672
00:42:27,545 --> 00:42:29,111
- Hey, Jake.
- Hey.

673
00:42:29,285 --> 00:42:31,461
- Cody.

674
00:42:31,636 --> 00:42:34,377
Too bad about Sam's place, huh?

675
00:42:34,552 --> 00:42:37,032
- Yeah.

676
00:42:37,206 --> 00:42:39,034
- Clears the way for the mall
though, doesn't it?

677
00:42:39,208 --> 00:42:40,166
- Mm-hmm.

678
00:42:40,340 --> 00:42:42,603
- [Clears throat]

679
00:42:42,777 --> 00:42:45,693
Cody...

680
00:42:45,867 --> 00:42:48,174
Where were you yesterday
before the dance?

681
00:42:48,348 --> 00:42:52,178
[Balls smacking]

682
00:42:52,352 --> 00:42:55,094
- Well, here I was

683
00:42:55,268 --> 00:42:57,444
figuring you'd come
to talk to me about the ranch.

684
00:42:57,618 --> 00:43:01,100
How you'd thought about it
and all.

685
00:43:03,276 --> 00:43:05,321
[Sighs]
Yesterday...

686
00:43:05,495 --> 00:43:08,498
I was, uh, right here

687
00:43:08,673 --> 00:43:11,589
playing pool, right Jake?

688
00:43:14,635 --> 00:43:16,332
So...

689
00:43:16,506 --> 00:43:19,205
The ranch... name your price.

690
00:43:19,379 --> 00:43:22,034
[Ball hits pocket]

691
00:43:22,208 --> 00:43:23,557
- What do you want it for?

692
00:43:23,731 --> 00:43:26,386
You gonna burn it down
when I say no?

693
00:43:26,560 --> 00:43:30,259
- I'm a businessman, Bobby,
not some firebug.

694
00:43:31,347 --> 00:43:34,089
- Nice shot.

695
00:43:34,263 --> 00:43:35,613
See ya, Jake.

696
00:43:37,310 --> 00:43:40,618
[Door opens and closes]

697
00:43:43,708 --> 00:43:46,624
- Hey, darling. Hey.

698
00:43:46,798 --> 00:43:48,538
Ok, I'm not going to
hurt you, all right.

699
00:43:48,713 --> 00:43:51,106
I'm just going to try
and check your leg here, ok?

700
00:43:51,280 --> 00:43:52,455
[Growling]

701
00:43:52,630 --> 00:43:56,372
[Snarls]

702
00:43:59,506 --> 00:44:01,987
- Peanut butter and jelly?
My specialty.

703
00:44:02,161 --> 00:44:03,031
[Panting]

704
00:44:06,382 --> 00:44:09,559
What?

705
00:44:09,734 --> 00:44:11,387
Ok, if you don't like 'em
together,

706
00:44:11,561 --> 00:44:13,085
I can make grilled cheese.

707
00:44:13,259 --> 00:44:15,348
- Come here, come here,
Madison.

708
00:44:15,522 --> 00:44:18,438
Know what. I just want you
to stand here, ok.

709
00:44:18,612 --> 00:44:21,484
Just don't move and keep talking
to mama here like you were.

710
00:44:21,659 --> 00:44:23,661
Ok?
- Ok.

711
00:44:25,184 --> 00:44:26,620
- Hey.

712
00:44:26,794 --> 00:44:30,711
You all right?
[Wolf moans]

713
00:44:30,885 --> 00:44:35,368
It's ok. It's ok.

714
00:44:35,542 --> 00:44:38,414
It's ok.

715
00:44:38,588 --> 00:44:39,502
- Keep talking. That's good.

716
00:44:39,677 --> 00:44:41,766
- Yeah, you're ok.

717
00:44:41,940 --> 00:44:44,551
- There you go.
- You're all right.

718
00:44:48,207 --> 00:44:49,687
Good girl.

719
00:44:55,518 --> 00:44:57,912
[Tapping keys]

720
00:44:58,086 --> 00:45:02,787
Dear dawn, you know how people
say nothing lasts forever?

721
00:45:02,961 --> 00:45:05,180
Let me tell you,
it's so true, girl.

722
00:45:05,354 --> 00:45:07,705
Things have changed a lot
since we came here.

723
00:45:07,879 --> 00:45:09,184
Dad's doing great,

724
00:45:09,358 --> 00:45:11,360
although he's crazy busy
these days.

725
00:45:11,534 --> 00:45:13,623
He comes in after working
all day,

726
00:45:13,798 --> 00:45:16,888
eats dinner and stays up
all night guarding the animals.

727
00:45:17,062 --> 00:45:20,500
We had two mustangs killed.
It was awful.

728
00:45:20,674 --> 00:45:22,676
Dad only sleeps
a couple of hours

729
00:45:22,850 --> 00:45:24,199
right when the sun
comes up.

730
00:45:24,373 --> 00:45:25,635
I don't know how he does it,

731
00:45:25,810 --> 00:45:27,725
but I don't care because
he's happier

732
00:45:27,899 --> 00:45:29,378
than I've ever seen him
in a long time.

733
00:45:29,552 --> 00:45:31,163
I've changed too.

734
00:45:31,337 --> 00:45:34,166
When we got here, I'd never been
on a horse before.

735
00:45:34,340 --> 00:45:36,690
And now you can't get me
off one.

736
00:45:36,864 --> 00:45:38,474
I spend as much time
as I can riding,

737
00:45:38,648 --> 00:45:40,215
and even Hank says
I'm turning into

738
00:45:40,389 --> 00:45:41,739
a pretty good horsewoman.

739
00:45:41,913 --> 00:45:44,219
That's what he calls me.
Can you imagine?

740
00:45:44,393 --> 00:45:47,396
I haven't bought
a cowboy hat yet, but who knows.

741
00:45:47,570 --> 00:45:49,747
Maybe I will.
Would you still talk to me?

742
00:45:53,881 --> 00:45:57,363
And I wish you could see
the wolf pups.

743
00:45:57,537 --> 00:46:00,409
They're growing so fast!
Believe me, they're adorable!

744
00:46:00,583 --> 00:46:04,674
And a big responsibility.

745
00:46:04,849 --> 00:46:07,112
Emily says that without
their mom

746
00:46:07,286 --> 00:46:08,853
to teach them
for the time being,

747
00:46:09,027 --> 00:46:11,246
it's up to us
to keep them active and strong.

748
00:46:11,420 --> 00:46:14,249
She leaves most of that to me.
Well, Tim and me.

749
00:46:14,423 --> 00:46:16,425
He's got a really good way
with animals,

750
00:46:16,599 --> 00:46:18,645
and Emily says
we make a good team.

751
00:46:18,819 --> 00:46:20,908
I think all three of us do.

752
00:46:21,082 --> 00:46:24,216
Five, if you count
Montana and Indiana.

753
00:46:24,390 --> 00:46:25,783
[Low growling]

754
00:46:25,957 --> 00:46:28,263
As much as I love
working with them,

755
00:46:28,437 --> 00:46:29,743
I don't like to think about

756
00:46:29,917 --> 00:46:31,527
Dakota getting well
for very long.

757
00:46:31,701 --> 00:46:33,747
I know she needs to take
her family back to their home,

758
00:46:33,921 --> 00:46:36,489
but I don't know
what I'll do when they're gone.

759
00:46:36,663 --> 00:46:39,492
[Sighs]
Onto other things.

760
00:46:39,666 --> 00:46:40,798
Remember our favorite spot
at Zuma beach

761
00:46:40,972 --> 00:46:42,669
near lifeguard stand 40?

762
00:46:42,843 --> 00:46:45,019
Well, I'm a long way from there,
chick,

763
00:46:45,193 --> 00:46:47,979
but I do have a favorite spot
to swim on hot afternoons.

764
00:46:48,153 --> 00:46:49,850
And we get plenty of those,
I can tell you.

765
00:46:50,024 --> 00:46:51,460
There's not a lifeguard,

766
00:46:51,634 --> 00:46:53,375
but I don't really need one
with Tim around.

767
00:46:55,987 --> 00:46:58,946
Oh, and my dad's
